MT C1.4 Lebesgue Measure

Posted on 2025-10-01 In Mathematics , Measure Theory

Chapter 1.4 Lebesgue Measure

Proposition 1.4.1 [Regularity] - Let A be a Lebesgue measurable subset of ℝd. Then,

  • λ(A) = inf {λ(U) : U is open and A ⊆ U}, and
  • λ(A) = sup {λ(K) : K is compact and K ⊆ A}.

Lemma 1.4.2 [Property of half open cubes] - Each open subset of ℝd is the union of a countable disjoint collection of half-open cubes, each of which is of the form given by {(x1, …, xd) : ji2−k ≤ xi < (ji + 1)2−k for i = 1, …, d}. for some integers j1, …, jd and some positive integer k.

Proposition 1.4.3 - Lebesgue measure is the only measure on (ℝd, ℬ(ℝd)) that assigns to each d-dimensional interval, or even to each half-open cube its volume.

Definition 1 [Translate] - The translate of A ⊆ ℝd by x ∈ ℝd is A + x defined by A + x = {y ∈ ℝd : y = a + x for some a ∈ A}. Proposition 1.4.4 [Translation invariance] - Lebesgue outer measure on ℝd is translation invariant, in the sense that if x ∈ ℝd and A ⊆ ℝd, then λ*(A) = λ*(A + x). Furthermore, a subset B of ℝd is Lebesgue measurable iff B + x is Lebesgue measurable.

Proposition 1.4.5 - Let μ be a nonzero measure on (ℝd, ℬ(ℝd)) that is finite on the bounded Borel subsets of ℝd and is translation invariant, in the sense that μ(A) = μ(A + x) holds for each A in ℬ(ℝd) and each x in ℝd. Then there is a positive number c such that μ(A) = cλ(A) holds for each A in ℬ(ℝd).

Definition 2 [The Cantor Set] - Let K0 be the interval [0, 1]. Form K1 by removing from K0 the interval (1/3, 2/3). Continue this procedure, forming Kn by removing from Kn − 1 the open middle third of each of the intervals making up Kn − 1. The Cantor set is the set of points that remain; thus K = ∩nKn.

  • K is closed and bounded and has no interior points and Lebesgue measure 0.

  • The cardinality of K is that of the continuum.

    • sketch of proof : a sequence {zn} of 0's and 1's is assigned the number , which is a bijection of the set of all such sequences onto K.

      Employ the ternary representation: [Example] 1 = 1(0.22…); 0 = 0.00…; 1/3 = 0.1(0.022…); 2/3 = 0.2(0.122…).

      The initial interval K0 = [0, 1] followed by K1 = [0, 0.1] ∪ [0.2, 1]. Thus, the removal can be viewed to eliminate all numbers with the first digit after the radix point which is 1.[*]

      The remaining points within K are the points with all digits excluding 1, implying the digit can simply be 0 or 2. Hence, we can express each element within K by a sequence zn of 0 or 1 as . To analyze the cardinality of all {zn}'s, we can construct the sequence as follows and assume it is countable: we can select a sequence {an} such that an ≠ znn. Then, the sequence must be excluded in this set, contradicting the countability. Hence, the cardinality of {zn}'s is that of continuum, so is that of K.

Proposition 1.4.7 - The Cantor set is a compact set that has the cardinality of the continuum but has Lebesgue measure of zero.

Theorem 1.4.9 - There is a subset of ℝ, and in fact of the interval (0, 1), that is not Lebesgue measurable.

  • proof : Define an equivalence relation ∼ satisfying x ∼ y ⇔ x − y ∈ ℚ. Based on the axiom of choice, we can form a subset E of (0, 1) whose elements are the representatives of all equivalent classes. Now we need to prove E is not Lebesgue measurable.

    Given a sequence {rn}, an enumeration of the rational numbers in (−1, 1), define En = E + rn. Hence,

    • En are disjoint,
    • ∪nEn is included in (−1, 2), and
    • (0, 1) is included in ∪nEn.

    Suppose E is Lebesgue measurable. λ(∪nEn) = ∑nλ(En). If λ(E) = 0, λ(∪nEn) = 0 contradicts λ(E) ≥ 1. On the other hand, if λ(E) > 0, λ(E) → ∞. Therefore, E is not Lebesgue measurable.

Definition 3 [Diff] - Diff(A) is the subset of ℝ defined by Diff(A) = {x − y : x ∈ A and y ∈ A}. Proposition 1.4.10 - Let A be a Lebesgue measurable subset of ℝ such that λ(A) > 0. Then Diff(A) includes an open interval that contains 0.

  • proof : There exists a open set U and a compact set K such that K ⊆ A ⊆ U and λ(U) < 2λ(K). Then, we can assert that the distance between points in K and the ones in Uc is positive and lower bounded. Therefore, ∃ε > 0, ∀|x| < ε, x + K ⊆ U. If x + K were disjoint from K, then 2λ(K) = λ(K) + λ(x + K) = λ(K ∪ (x + K)) ≤ λ(U), contradicting λ(U) < 2λ(K). Therefore, x ∈ Diff(K) ⇒ (−ε, ε) ⊆ Diff(K) ⊆ Diff(A).

Proposition 1.4.11 - There is a subset A of ℝ such that each Lebesgue measurable set that is included in A or in Ac has Lebesgue measure zero.

  • proof : Define subsets G, G0, and G1 of ℝ by Define a relation ∼ as x ∼ y ⇔ x − y ∈ G. Based on the axiom of choice, form a subset E of ℝ that contains exactly one representative of each equivalent class. Let A = E + G0.

    Assume there ∃ a subset B of A such that λ(B) > 0. Then, ∃ε > 0 (−ε, ε) ⊆ Diff(B) ⊆ Diff(A). G1 is dense in and intersects (−ε, ε), so there ∃x ∈ G1 and |x| < ε. Besides, x = e1 − e2 + g0 ∈ A where e1, e2 ∈ E ⇒ e1 − e2 ∈ E and g0 ∈ G0. Therefore, ∃g1 ∈ G1 such that g1 = e1 − e2 + g0 ⇒ e1 = e2, g1 = g0, leading to the contradiction. Therefore, A must have Lebesgue measurable set whose measure is zero.

    In contrast, we can construct implying the same result. Therefore, the assertion holds.

Normed Linear Spaces

DEF : A norm 𝒩 defined on a linear space 𝒳 is satisfying the following properties:

  • 𝒩(x) ≥ 0 for ∀x ∈ 𝒳, 𝒩(x) = 0 ⇔ x = 0.
  • α ∈ 𝕂, x ∈ 𝒳, 𝒩(αx) = |α|𝒩(x).
  • x, y ∈ 𝒳, 𝒩(x + y) ≤ 𝒩(x) + 𝒩(y).

OBS : |‖x‖−‖y‖| ≤ ‖x − y‖, ‖ − x‖ = ‖x‖.

DEF : A metric d defined as d : 𝒳 × 𝒳 → ℝ+ by d(x, y) = ‖x − y‖ with

  • d(x, y) ≥ 0, d(x, y) = 0 ⇔ x = y.
  • d(x, y) = d(y, x).
  • d(x, z) ≤ d(x, y) + d(y, z).

DEF : Norms 𝒩1, 𝒩2 are equivalent if ∃0 < c < ∞, .[Equivalence]

Product Space - (𝒳1, 𝒩1) and (𝒳2, 𝒩2) are the two normed linear spaces. The product space defined as 𝒳1 × 𝒳2 = {(x1, x2) : x1 ∈ 𝒳1, x2 ∈ 𝒳2} is a linear space.

Closure - 𝒴 ⊆ 𝒳 is a linear subspace, and then is the closure of 𝒴 such that .

Quotient Space - 𝒴 ⊆ 𝒳 is a closed linear subspace, 𝒳|𝒴 = {[x] : x ∈ 𝒳}, [x] = {z ∈ 𝒳, z − x ∈ 𝒴}. ‖[x]‖ = inf {‖z‖ : z ∈ [x]} is a norm in 𝒳|𝒴.

DEF : (xk, k ≥ 1) is a Cauchy sequence if ∀ϵ > 0, ∃k0, ∀j, k ≥ k0 such that ‖xj − xk‖ < ϵ.

DEF : 𝒳 is complete if every Cauchy sequence converges.

DEF : Banach space is a normed complete linear space.

Quotient Spaces

DEF : For a linear subspace 𝒴 ∈ 𝒳, x ∼ y if x − y ∈ 𝒴. [Equivalence]

  • x ∼ x
  • x ∼ y ⇒ y ∼ x
  • x ∼ y, y ∼ z ⇒ x ∼ z

DEF : (𝒳 modulo 𝒴) 𝒳|𝒴 = {[x] = {y ∈ 𝒴 : y ∼ x} : x ∈ 𝒳}.

  • [x] + [y] = [x + y]

DEF : (Linear maps) 𝒯 : 𝒳 → 𝒳* is a linear map if 1) 𝒯(x + y) = 𝒯(x) + 𝒯(y) and 2) 𝒯(αx) = α𝒯(x).

  • 𝒴 ⊆ 𝒳 is linear subspace, and then 𝒯(𝒴) = {𝒯(x) : x ∈ 𝒴} is a linear subspace.
  • 𝒴* ⊆ 𝒳* is a linear subspace, and then 𝒯−1(𝒴*) = {x ∈ 𝒳 : 𝒯(x) ∈ 𝒴*} is a linear space.

DEF : (Isomorph) 𝒳 and 𝒳* are isomorphic if ∃𝒯 : 𝒳 → 𝒳* bijection.

DEF : (Convex) 𝒦 ∈ 𝒳 is convex if x, y ∈ 𝒦, α ∈ [0, 1], αx + (1 − α)y ∈ 𝒦.

  • 𝒴1, 𝒴2 ∈ 𝒳 are convex subsets, and then 𝒴1 + 𝒴2 is convex.
  • 𝒦θ, θ ∈ ℐ are convex, and then ∩θ𝒦θ is convex.
  • 𝒦θ, θ ∈ ℐ are convex and totally ordered, and then ∪θ𝒦θ is convex.

Linear Spaces

DEF : 𝒳 is a linear space over a field 𝕂 (ℂ or ℝ) if 𝒳 is a set with 2 operations + and ⋅ (scalar multiplication).

  • +: x, y ∈ 𝒳 ⇒ x + y ∈ 𝒳
    • Commutative: x + y = y + x
    • Associative: x + (y + z) = x + y + z
    • Group: ∃0: 0 + x = x; ∃−x: −x + x = 0
  • ⋅ : x ∈ 𝒳, α, β ∈ 𝕂 ⇒ αx ∈ 𝒳
    • Commutative: (αβ)x = α(βx)
    • Distributive: (α + β)x = αx + βx, α(x + y) = αx + αy
    • 1: 1 ⋅ x = x

DEF : 𝒴 ⊆ 𝒳 is a linear subspace if x, y ∈ 𝒴, α ∈ 𝕂 such that αx + y ∈ 𝒴.

  • {𝒴θ : θ ∈ ℐ} is a set including linear subspace of 𝒳, then ∩θ ∈ ℐ𝒴θ is a linear subspace of 𝒳.

DEF : {𝒴θ, θ ∈ ℐ} is totally ordered if θ1, θ2 ∈ ℐ 𝒴θ1 ⊆ 𝒴θ2 or 𝒴θ1 ⊇ 𝒴θ2.

  • {𝒴θ : θ ∈ ℐ} is a totally ordered set including linear subspace of 𝒳, ∪θ ∈ ℐ𝒴θ is a linear space.

DEF : 𝒮 ⊆ 𝒳, linear span of 𝒮 is LS(𝒮) = ∩θ𝒴θ for 𝒴θ ⊇ 𝒮. [Smallest linear space containing S]

Seg03 - Eigenvalue and Eigenvector Decomposition of the Discrete Fourier Transform

Preliminaries

DEF : c(n) = col[c(0), …, c(N − 1)] ∈ ℂN is even iff c(n) = c(−n) and odd iff c(n) = −c(−n) with the definition of c(−n) = col[c(0), c(N − 1), …, c(1)].

Lemma 1 : There exists an orthogonal basis for ℂN consisting of v = [N/2] + 1 even sequences and N − v odd sequences.

  • Proof : An orthogonal basis can be constructed as follows: For N being even, there exists u(n) = col[0, …, 0, 1, 0, …, 0]. So there are (N − 2)/2 + 2 = N/2 + 1 even sequences. In the meantime, the number of odd sequences is (N − 2)/2 = N/2 − 1.

    For N being odd, there exists u(n) = col[0, …, 0, 1, 1, 0, …, 0]. So there are (N − 1)/2 + 1 = (N + 1)/2 even sequences. In the meantime, the number of odd sequences is (N − 1)/2.

    Therefore, there are even sequences and ⌈N/2 − 1⌉ = ⌊(N − 1)/2⌋ odd sequences whenever N is odd or even.

Lemma 2 : The eigenvectors of F are either even or odd sequences.

  • Proof : Assume the eigenvector of F is x such that Fx = λx. we have . The orthogonality yields Thus, αi = 0 for λ ∈ {−j, j} and βj = 0 for λ ∈ {−1, 1}. So x is either odd or even.

Digital Computation of the Fractional Fourier Transform (1996)

The FrFT has been widely used in a lot of fields, especially in communications. However, the operations with respect to the continuous domain can lead to considerable computational complexity.
